y in that role (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrothermal aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated hydrothermal temperature and pressure", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "hydrothermal mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "submarine hydrothermal system; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-carbon of alanine adds to formaldehyde in an aldol-type carbon-carbon bond-forming reaction, producing the beta-hydroxylated C4 amino acid threonine.", "reasoning": "Aubrey, Cleaves & Bada (2008) experimentally demonstrated alanine + formaldehyde -> threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions. The literature review identifies this as the second experimentally supported threonine-producing route and emphasizes formaldehyde availability from hydrothermal carbon reduction chemistry and alanine supply from multiple upstream sources (Aubrey, Cleaves & Bada, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical wet-dry peptide bond formation incorporating threonine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces or in concentrated prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative condensation joins alanine and threonine into a dipeptide during iterative concentration and drying cycles.", "reasoning": "The system instructions require the network to flow into biochemical assembly. Threonine produced by either literature-supported route enters the amino acid pool and participates in peptide bond formation under prebiotic wet-dry cycling, a standard downstream biochemical assembly step. This reaction is not part of the threonine synthesis literature per se but is necessary to 