mbient to moderate hydrothermal", "catalyst": "elemental iron", "aqueous": true, "other": "70 degrees C; Fe0/Fe2+-rich reducing system as reported for hydrothermal-style amino acid generation"}, "mechanism": "Hydroxylamine-derived nitrogen is incorporated into the alpha-keto acid under iron-mediated reduction to furnish alanine.", "reasoning": "The review explicitly identifies reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine in the presence of iron as an upstream route to alanine and ties it to hydrothermal settings. This step is therefore directly aligned with the literature-supported precursor logic for the hydrothermal alanine -> threonine pathway (Muchowska et al., 2019, as summarized in the curated review)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated temperature and pressure characteristic of submarine hydrothermal systems", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mineral vent surfaces; no specific catalyst documented for the threonine-forming step", "aqueous": true, "other": "submarine hydrothermal conditions; product expected to be racemic threonine/allo-threonine mixture rather than enantiopure material"}, "mechanism": "Aldol-type C-C bond formation between the alanine alpha-carbon and formaldehyde produces the beta-hydroxy amino acid skeleton of threonine.", "reasoning": "This is one of the two experimentally demonstrated threonine-forming reactions in the supplied literature. Aubrey, Cleaves & Bada (2008) reported alanine + formaldehyde -> threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions. The review also notes selectivity and stereochemistry remain open questions, so the network avoids unsupported homochirality claims even though the literature summary names L-threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface cyanosul